<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 93 / Asil Nadir in Cyprus: Getaway route was via France
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AIRCRAFT identified by Turkish Cypriot officials as having flown Mr Asil
Nadir to Cyprus took off from an airfield owned by British Aerospace on
Monday afternoon.
Mr Nadir, however, boarded that aircraft in France. It is thought he made
his way to France in a light aircraft from another airfield at Compton Abbas
in Dorset, taking advantage of new simplified EC passport procedures.
Compton Abbas airfield refused to comment on reports that a Piper PA34 had
taken off with Mr Nadir. BAe refused to disclose who owned the aircraft
which flew to Cyprus via France but confirmed it had departed from its
airfield in Hatfield, Hertfordshire.
The company said it had given the Serious Fraud Office full details of the
flight plan, but said it did not know who chartered the aircraft.
According to the US Federal Aviation Administration, the Cessna 500 Citation
which landed in northern Cyprus is owned by a US company called Flamingo
500, whose president is Mr Michael G. Hamlin. The FAA said one of the
alleged pilots - Mr Alexander Marc Tai - was licensed in the US.
BAe confirmed last night that Mr Hamlin was a regular customer of Hatfield.
</TEXT>
