<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 93 / Clinton pledges to work for Gatt deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE US and the EC yesterday renewed their commitment to completing
negotiations on the Uruguay Round of world trade liberalisation talks,
promising a successful conclusion by the end of the year.
President Bill Clinton said after talks with Mr Poul Rasmussen, the Danish
prime minister, and Mr Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission,
that the US was 'prepared to take a lot of trouble to get it done.'
He added that he wanted to have tangible progress before the Tokyo summit of
the Group of Seven leading industrial nations in July.
Mr Delors said the talks concentrated on issues of market access, and set an
even more ambitious deadline: he hoped for enough agreement to warrant full
multilateral negotiations within the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade
in Geneva by the time ministers of the 24-nation Organisation for Economic
Co-operation and Development meet in Paris in early June.
Mr Delors said he was looking for concessions from the US in the areas of
customs tariffs, textiles, steel, telecommunications and services.
'This is not only in the interests of the European countries but also in the
interests of the developing countries,' he said, noting progress had already
been made 'not only in the mood but also in procedure and substance.'
Mr Clinton has shown a renewed energy in his pursuit of the Gatt
negotiations over the last week, just as some free trade advocates were
beginning to despair that he might be bowing to the strong protectionist
sentiments among some members of his own Democratic party in Congress.
Some foreign trade analysts, too, have doubted the Clinton administration's
commitment to multilateral free trade negotiations because of its
simultaneous pursuit of aggressive bilateral trade measures.
But the Clinton administration argues that the two approaches are not
incompatible: that tough enforcement of trade laws and international
agreements is not just necessary to placate domestic opinion, but actually
helpful to the pursuit of a new and more liberal Gatt.
In particular, US trade officials distinguish efforts to gain access to
markets they regard as unfairly closed to US goods and services, notably in
Japan, from efforts to close US markets to imports.
</TEXT>
