<HEADLINE>
FT  08 MAY 93 / Ciampi wins confidence vote
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ROME
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Carlo Azeglio Ciampi, the former governor of the Bank of Italy, last
night won a parliamentary vote of confidence in his new role as head of the
country's 52nd post-war government.
His firm commitment to carry out electoral reform before the summer muted
opposition and paved the way for a large number of abstentions. He was
backed outright by the outgoing four-party coalition plus the Referendum
Movement led by Mr Mario Segni and the Radicals.
There were 309 votes in the Chamber of Deputies for Mr Ciampi, 185
abstensions and only 60 against him - the No votes representing the
neo-fascist MSI and the hardline communists, Reconstructed Communism. The
Network (La Rete), the clean government movement, refused to attend the
debate.
The new prime minister was frequently reminded during the two-day debate of
the difficulties of a non-parliamentarian dealing with parliament and of the
fragile majority behind the government.
Mr Ciampi's non-political origins in a country where the parties have been
disgraced by scandal is a mixed blessing, as shown by the ambiguous feelings
among members of parliament. The debate revealed a clear split between
parties that want the government to last at least until next year and those
pressing for fresh elections directly after new electoral laws are approved.
The Christian Democrats and Socialists, the backbone of the majority behind
the Ciampi government, insisted there should be no time limit. They fear
facing early elections in a state of disarray. By contrast, the former
communist Party of the Democratic Left (PDS), the Republicans, the populist
Lombard League, the Greens, as well as the Referendum Movement, claimed the
government's sole task was to comply with the wishes of the electorate as
expressed in the April 18 referendum.
The referendum introduced a system of majority voting for two thirds of
seats in the Senate - the upper house of parliament - the remainder being
covered by proportional representation.
The latter parties openly threatened to carry out spoiling action should the
government try to prolong its life beyond the introduction of electoral
reform.
Mr Segni, leader of the Referendum Movement, claimed such legislation could
be presented to the government in days. He has already drawn up proposals
for the Chamber of Deputies similar to those endorsed in the referendum for
the Senate.
Yesterday, Mr Ciampi, in reply to the debate, assured parliament he staked
his prestige on being able to oversee such reform before the summer recess.
He also warned that the process of political realignment risked further
mutation as a result of the June 6 municipal and regional elections,
involving 11m voters.
</TEXT>
<XX>
