<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Tory humiliation in Newbury: Big gains for Liberal Democrats
in local elections as Conservative vote collapses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS and JOHN WILLMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A SENSATIONAL defeat in the Newbury by-election and a collapse in the
Conservative vote in the shire counties last night dealt a humiliating blow
to the authority of Mr John Major's government.
In Newbury, the Liberal Democrats scored a spectacular victory in the
by-election called following the death of Mrs Judith Chaplin. In a seat held
by the Conservatives since 1924, Mr David Rendel, the Liberal Democrat,
overturned the government's previous 12,357 majority to win the seat by a
massive 22,055 votes.
Mr Julian Davidson, the Conservative candidate, saw his party's share of the
vote slump from 55.9 per cent to less than 30 per cent. Mr Rendel's share
jumped from 37.3 per cent to 64 per cent. As expected, Labour's vote was
squeezed to a mere 1,151 votes, losing the party its deposit.
The swing of 28.4 per cent recorded against the government compared to April
1992 was the largest seen in the succession of by-election defeats suffered
by the Conservatives since 1979.
The Newbury result cuts to 19 the government's majority in the House of
Commons at a time when its authority has already been seriously undermined
by the Conservative backbench battle over ratification of the Maastricht
treaty.
In the first serious test of public opinion since the general election, the
Conservatives were routed in their traditional heartlands, losing control of
all but one of the 16 county councils they held in England and Wales.
During a night of unremitting gloom for the government, Mr Paddy Ashdown's
Liberal Democrats emerged as the biggest gainers, winning more than 350
extra county council seats as well as the by-election. The scale of last
night's Conservative defeats will face Mr Major with renewed calls for a
large-scale cabinet reshuffle.
Mr Norman Lamont, whose claim that the economic recovery was under way
formed the centrepiece of the Conservative campaign in Newbury, will again
find a question mark over his hold on the chancellorship.
Buckinghamshire is now the only county to remain under overall Conservative
control. More than half the councils in England and Wales will be under no
overall control.
The Liberal Democrats, the biggest gainers of the night, held the Isle of
Wight, and won control of Somerset and Cornwall. The party won more than 300
seats across the country.
Kent was one of the first councils to slip from Tory control - the first
time since the inception of the county in 1889. Essex voters also deserted
the Conservatives early in the night, with the loss of 25 seats to Labour
and the Liberal Democrats.
This was swiftly followed by the loss of Conservative control in Dorset,
East Sussex, West Sussex, Suffolk, Hampshire and Surrey, where the party was
defending a 34-seat majority.
Sir Norman Fowler, Conservative party chairman, described the results as a
'protest vote at a time when the memory of recession is still fresh'.
Provisional figures suggested that the Conservative share of the national
vote had slumped to 31 per cent, Labour's had increased to 41 per cent and
the Liberal Democrats' had risen to 24 per cent.
Mr Ashdown said the outcome marked an 'astonishing' and 'a devastating blow
to the Conservatives'. Calling for increased co-operation between the
opposition parties, he added: 'It's absolutely clear that the country has no
confidence in a government.'
Labour gained control of Northamptonshire, and strengthened its hold over
Lancashire. Although Labour's gains were more modest than those of the
Liberal Democrats, a spokesman said the party would for the first time hold
more county council seats than the Conservatives.
A Labour spokesman said: 'It is an appalling indictment of this government.
This is the end of the Tory shires.'
 --------------------------------------
Newbury by-election
 --------------------------------------
Candidate                       Vote
 --------------------------------------
David Rendel (Lib Dem)        37,590
Julian Davidson (Con)         15,535
Steve Billcliffe (Lab)         1,151
Lib Dem gain        Majority: 22,055
