<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Bosnian Serbs face Belgrade supply blockade
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT MAUTHNER, JUREK MARTIN and DAVID GARDNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, WASHINGTON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
SERBIA took swift action against the defiant Bosnian Serbs yesterday,
announcing a halt to all but humanitarian supplies across the border, as
President Bill Clinton warned that the Bosnian crisis could threaten the
stability of Europe.
Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic moved to hamper the Bosnian Serbs'
fighting capacity after they spurned his plea to back the international
peace plan for Bosnia.
Mr Clinton described the Bosnian Serbs' decision - made in defiance of
possible air strikes by the US and its allies - as a 'grave disappointment'.
He said their assembly's decision to put the peace plan before the Bosnian
Serb people in a May 15-16 referendum was a 'delaying tactic' to consolidate
their gains in the 13-month-old civil war with Bosnian Moslems and Croats.
The assembly's refusal to endorse the peace plan was decided by an
overwhelming majority of 51 votes to 2 with 12 abstentions early yesterday
morning.
In a clear message to his European allies, Mr Clinton said he had instructed
Mr Warren Christopher, the secretary of state, to be 'insistent' during his
current tour of European capitals that tougher and collective measures be
agreed soon.
Mr Christopher vowed to concentrate efforts to end the war exclusively on
punitive measures against the Serbs and said he was no longer pursuing a
United Nations peace plan. Speaking in Bonn after meeting German chancellor
Helmut Kohl and Mr Klaus Kinkel, the foreign minister, Mr Christopher said
the failure of the Bosnian Serb parliament to back the peace plan meant that
option was now closed.
'Until today we were basically discussing two different tracks. Now, we're
focusing on a single track,' he said.
The White House later said that a new UN Security Council Resolution would
be required if further action in the form of air strikes or other military
measures were to be taken.
The Security Council held urgent consultations last night in an atmosphere
of deepening crisis. It decided unanimously to designate Sarajevo, the
Bosnian capital, and the Moslem enclaves of Zepa, Gorazde, Bihac and Tuzla,
as 'safe areas' which would be patrolled and, if necessary, defended by UN
troops.
Mr Haris Silajdzic, the Bosnian Moslem foreign minister, claimed in
Washington yesterday that 40,000 people would be 'massacred' in the besieged
town of Zepa if the international community did not intervene in Bosnia's
civil war. Bosnian Serb forces have refused to allow UN observers to visit
Zepa to investigate Bosnian government charges that a full-scale Serbian
assault had been launched.
If Serbia's decision to halt supplies to the Bosnian Serbs is effectively
carried out, it will starve the Bosnian Serb militia of the weapons and fuel
needed to pursue the fight against the republic's Moslems and Croats.
Branding the Bosnian Serb assembly's decision as irresponsible, the Serbian
government in Belgrade said: 'Aid to the Bosnian Serb republic should in
future be reduced to just food and medicines. . . . Reasons no longer exist
for further assistance in money, fuel, raw materials etc.' Diplomats in
Belgrade said the move was a sign of the Serbian government's desire to halt
the war and stave off the threat of western military intervention.
Belgrade's move came after Mr John Major, the prime minister, and Lord Owen,
the European Community mediator, urged Serbia to seal off its border with
Bosnia.
Bosnia on the brink, Page 2
</TEXT>
