<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Patten ready to press on with
testing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FRESH BLOWS to the government's plans for testing have increased the
pressure on Mr John Patten, the education secretary, but left him still
determined to press ahead.
Although the courts have not proved a way of preventing the looming boycott
by teachers, and the traditional 'divide and rule' approach to the teachers'
unions has collapsed, Mr Patten and other ministers insist in public that
they want this year's tests to proceed.
In private, however, both ministers and officials recognise that there will
be disruption, and that the only question is its scale.
One said yesterday: 'The tests will be disrupted, that is now discounted.'
Another said: 'There won't be many league tables.'
Although the changes made to testing in Scotland as a result of pressure
from teachers and parents have been urged on ministers as a way of avoiding
the likely shambles, elsewhere in government there is little enthusiasm for
what has resulted there.
Ministerial determination not to change course has been bolstered by the
reaction to the advertising of leaflets about testing - the number of
responses asking for copies of the leaflets will be released in the next
couple of weeks. A further 1.3 million copies will be issued with child
benefit.
One official said: 'It is now clear that the government is prepared to
muddle through. We are locked into our position.'
The government seems to believe the worst is behind it. The resignations of
two key advisers from the School Examinations and Assessment Council this
week are seen as a 'nuisance' rather than a more serious difficulty, and the
teachers' plans on the curriculum are seen as simply a matter for Sir Ron
Dearing's review.
Deep-rooted Tory dislike of the educational establishment has muted much
criticism of Mr Patten, although some ministerial colleagues have privately
expressed surprise that Mr Patten seems to have courted confrontation rather
than tried to avoid it.
</TEXT>
<XX>
