<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Hospitals fail to meet cash target
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GOVERNMENT programme to encourage hospitals to make money from activities
such as retail services has fallen far short of its financial targets, a
National Audit Office report shows today, Alan Pike writes.
The income generation scheme was introduced in 1988 and the government hoped
it would raise Pounds 75m a year. According to the report, however, health
authorities and hospitals generated only Pounds 25m in 1991-92.
Even so, the NAO believes income generation has 'significant potential' in
the National Health Service and says that, in principle, the Pounds 75m
target should be attained.
It believes one reason for the failure to met targets so far has been
managers giving their first priority to introducing the 1991 health service
reforms.
Income Generation in the NHS, National Audit Office. HMSO. Pounds 7.40.
</TEXT>
