<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Local Government Elections: Tories eclipsed by Lib Dems -
Higher-than-usual turnout as voters reject recovery claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Conservatives had a disastrous day yesterday. They now retain control of
only one county - Buckinghamshire.
Once 44 of the 47 councils had announced complete results, the Conservatives
bore a net loss of 452 seats, with a net gain for Labour of 86, and a big
net gain for the Liberal Democrats of 363. In Wales, Plaid Cymru gained 12,
mostly from Labour.
The Liberal Democrats were boosted by the fact that the last county council
elections - in 1989 - came as the party's fortunes reached their nadir
following the merger of the Liberals and the Social Democrats. In those
contests, the Conservatives gained 77 seats across the country, and Labour
67.
Turnout varied across the country, but was healthy by the standards of
county council elections, at around 40 per cent, according to the
Association of County Councils.
Psychologically embarrassing results for the Conservatives came from a line
of south coast counties.
They lost overall control of Kent, Hampshire, and both East and West Sussex,
where the Liberal Democrats became the largest party. They also relinquished
control of Surrey, Hertfordshire, Lincolnshire and Warwickshire.
Essex, which had entered election mythology as the centre for the
Conservatives' victory in last year's general election, inflicted 22 losses
on the party. They were still marginally the strongest party with 35,
compared with 32 for Labour and 30 for the Liberal Democrats. Mr Bill Dixon
Smith, chairman of the Association of County Councils, who represented a
seat near Colchester, was a casualty.
East Anglia, basking in prosperity in 1989, repeated the pattern for the
south-east with the Conservatives losing control of Cambridgeshire, Norfolk
and Suffolk.
The Liberal Democrats' gains were greatest in their traditional stronghold
of the south-west. They gained Cornwall, and Somerset, which had previously
been controlled by the Conservatives, with a gain of 21 seats while the
Tories lost 18. The Liberal Democrats now have 41 seats to the
Conservatives' 13.
They wrested control of Dorset from the Conservatives, with a gain of 17, to
become the largest single party with 38 seats to the Conservatives' 29.
Devon produced a spectacular swing to the Liberal Democrats, whose
representation rose from 11 to 41. The Conservatives suffered a fall from 56
to 18, while Labour advanced from 13 to 21.
In Cumbria, where the Conservatives had harboured outside hopes of taking
overall control, Labour, already the largest party, increased its tally by
one despite an embarrassing mistake when two of its existing councillors
failed to file nomination papers in time.
Labour held on to the councillors it already held, but made few gains, only
taking overall control of one new county, Northamptonshire, where it added
just five seats, with the Conservatives losing seven, and the Liberal
Democrats gaining three.
Unusual results included the former Monster Raving Loony Party candidate,
who deprived the Conservatives of a seat on Devon county council, while a
Green party councillor was elected in Oxfordshire. And one of Labour's
winning candidates in Northants was the wife of Lady Thatcher's cousin.
</TEXT>
<XX>
