<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Local Government Elections: Horse trading set to become norm
 -Higher-than-usual turnout as voters reject recovery claims
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ENGLISH local government moves into uncharted territory this morning.
Twenty-eight counties have no overall control - more than ever before. This
will have profound effects on the way individual counties run their affairs,
and on relationships between central and local government.
Formal pacts are unlikely to be the norm. Instead, the largest parties will
put forward programmes, and look for support on an issue-by-issue basis.
The two focal points for forging party alliances will be the appointment of
committee chairmen, expected soon, and the setting of the budget.
According to Mr Andrew Stunell, political officer for the Liberal Democrat
Councillors, his party will expect to be recognised as the policymakers in
the eight counties where it is now the largest party, as well as the three
where it holds overall control.
He said: 'There will be a number of Labour politicians who are having to
come to terms with what it will be like when we have got a reformed
constitution in this country. It's the norm in the rest of Europe and it's
not all that difficult when you start.'
Labour described speculation about 'Lab-Lib pacts' as 'basically
legitimate', and described them as 'the inevitable result of these
elections'.
For example, in Norfolk, where the Conservatives have lost overall control
for the first time since 1888 but remain the largest party, Labour will talk
to the Liberal Democrats on issues where they have common cause - these
include opposition to the closure of village schools, rural policies, and
applications for EC aid.
Conservatives will now be the third party on the Association of County
Councils, a body they are accustomed to dominating. The government can
expect concerted opposition from it.
County councils are responsible for implementing the national curriculum in
schools, so the news will be unwelcome for the government in its current
difficulties over testing.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
