<PROFILE>_AN-DEGCQAGAFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>930507
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Survey of Canadian Forest Products (9): The McDonald's way -
Profile / Abitibi-Price
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BETWEEN visits to customers and mills, a group of senior managers at
Abitibi-Price has been calling on companies as far removed from the
newsprint business as United Parcel Service, Hewlett-Packard and snack-food
maker Frito-Lay.
The Abitibi managers are hoping to learn some of the secrets which have made
these companies among the best performing and most admired in North American
business. Their task is to apply the lessons to the corporate culture and
financial performance of their own company.
Mr Ron Oberlander, Abitibi's chief executive, asserts that newsprint
producers will need to look inwards to boost profits over the next few
years, rather than rely on a surge in the marketplace. 'I don't see any
return to glory days,' Mr Oberlander says. 'This is going to remain a very
tough industry.'
The over-riding question for every newsprint maker in the years ahead, he
predicts, will be: 'Where are you in the cost curve?' As a result, he is
trying to hammer home the message that maximising cash flow and containing
costs are now the top priorities for Abitibi's 8,600 workers.
Abitibi made a start in 1992 by cutting the net cost of its newsprint by
CDollars 15 a tonne, and generating CDollars 175m in cash. In the first
three months of 1993, the combined operating profit of its 11 mills showed
the first quarterly year-on-year increase in five years.
Mr John Duncanson, forestry analyst at Sanwa McCarthy in Toronto, predicts
that Abitibi will be modestly profitable in 1993 after three consecutive
years of losses totalling CDollars 345m. 'I think they've got their act
together on the management side. 'But they still have a couple of hurdles to
go,' he says.
Mr John Johnson, analyst at Richardson Greenshields, forecasts a return to
profitability only in 1994.
One uncertainty still hanging over Abitibi is its ownership. Olympia &amp; York,
the crippled real estate developer, nominally has an 82 per cent stake. But
under O&amp;Y's debt restructuring, the shares are now controlled by a
consortium of international banks to which they were pledged as collateral
for a USDollars 2.5bn loan.
The banks are weighing their options. These include seeking a new
controlling shareholder, selling their shares in a public offering or
hanging on to them in the hope that the business recovery will increase
Abitibi's market value.
If Mr Oberlander has his way, Abitibi's new shareholders will find a vastly
different company from the one left behind by O&amp;Y.
Abitibi has turned its back on an ambitious but costly diversification drive
in the 1970s and 1980s to concentrate on its core business of groundwood
papers, especially newsprint. The company noted in its latest annual report:
'Frankly, it was always our core business that delivered the highest
earnings.'
Abitibi has sold, or is in the process of selling, several other businesses,
including its building products division, paper distributors and a coated
papers company.
It is also in the throes of reorganising the assets that remain. Three
business teams have been set up to deal with North American publishers,
commercial printers and international customers. Each of the 11 paper mills
is allocated to one of the divisions.
The most far-reaching changes however, are taking place at the mills
themselves. A recent study estimated that the company could have saved an
extra CDollars 45m in 1992 if each mill's performance during its best three
months could be sustained throughout the year.
Mr Oberlander, a Montrealer whose roots in the forestry industry go back to
his father's fibreboard mill, harps on the lessons which Abitibi can learn
from successful companies in other industries.
If McDonald's can produce consistently good French fries, Abitibi should be
able to do the same with groundwood papers, he insists. 'There's a
McDonald's way; there's got to be an Abitibi-Price way.'
The drive for consistently good products at low cost has begun not at
Abitibi's worst plant, but at its best, the Augusta mill in Georgia, which
is a joint venture with Thomson Corporation, the publishing and travel
group.
A team has been set up at Augusta under the regional manager and mill
manager with instructions to improve the mill's cash flow. Augusta now has
its own sales force and is taking over functions, such as invoicing and the
general ledger, previously handled by head office. Preventive maintenance is
getting more attention.
No matter how successful these efforts are, however, the extent and speed of
any commodity producer's recovery inevitably remain tied to border market
conditions over which it has little control.
Here the picture is mixed. 'Everything is tender,' Mr Oberlander says.
'We've been down so long that it's hard to believe up is possible.'
North American consumption for groundwood papers now appears to be on a
steady, through gradual, uptrend. But demand in Europe - especially the UK
and Germany - is still sagging. Abitibi's sales in offshore markets slumped
from CDollars 227m in 1991 - equal to 14 per cent of total revenues - to
CDollars 191m last year.
The company, which has a total capacity of almost 2m tonnes of newsprint and
460,000 tonnes of uncoated groundwood papers, a year, took another 20,000
tonnes out of production in April 1993, with the warning that 'further
downtime will be required in 1993 should present market conditions prevail.'
</TEXT>
