<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Survey of Canadian Forest Products (8): Focus switches to
high value - Profile / MacMillan Bloedel
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WORKERS in a sawmill in the British Columbia town of Port Alberni take
500-year old hemlock logs harvested from coastal rainforests and
painstakingly cut them into posts measuring 4 1/8 inches by 4 1/8 inches and
are typically 13ft long. The 'baby squares,' as they are called, are too
small for US homebuilders. The posts are specially cut for the Japanese
market, where expensive, light wood is prized in new homes, and beams are
exposed, rather than hidden behind the wall board.
Ancient trees are best for this market, because they provide high-quality
'clear' wood, free of knots and with highly compressed age rings that
produce a very fine grain. They also return a good value to the mill. The
'baby squares' command about Dollars 1,200 per thousand board feet, compared
with about Dollars 335 for the same measure of standard grade 2x4s used in
US homes.
When the wood reaches Japan, it might be milled further, cut into strips of
thin veneer to cover posts of the same dimension.
The Port Alberni mill and several others like it are owned and operated by
MacMillan Bloedel, British Columbia's largest integrated forest products
company. Last year MacMillan abandoned the traditional business of sawyering
 -making utility-grade lumber for the North American market - and has
focused its wood business on high-value products such as baby squares, and
trim, window casings and cedar-based patio products for sale in North
America and Europe.
The switch to specialty products has as much to do with natural resources as
it does with the market. Although timber in British Columbia is viewed as a
renewable resource, MacMillan Bloedel's supply of high value old-growth
coastal timber - mostly cedar, fir and hemlock - is declining.
The company's foresters estimate a 50-year supply of the old timber remains.
However, MacMillan's rights to cut the remaining old trees have become
entangled in controversy with environmental activists. and the company is at
risk of losing chunks of its projected harvest. Other BC timber companies
are facing similar conflicts.
Last month the company saw its potential cut in the scenic Clayoquot Sound
area of western Vancouver Island reduced to 600,000 cu m a year from 900,000
cu m in a controversial provincial decision. The potential impact to
MacMillan's bottom line is CDollars 10m, according to Mr Robert Findlay, the
company's president.
The impending 'loss of fibre,' as the company refers to the situation, has
prompted the company to do the most with what it has.
'There is less and less old growth timber,' says Mr Jim Chisholm, manager of
MacMillan Bloedel's North American lumber marketing. 'We have to take what
fibre we have and do more with it.' The solid wood business was MacMillan
Bloedel's profitable side last year, with half of its Dollars 3bn in sales
in lumber and building materials.
MacMillan often sells wood to a remanufacturer and then sells the resulting
product through its global distribution system. 'We sell the product twice,
and we make more money,' Mr Chisholm says.
The high value and remerch- andising strategy seems to be paying off. Where
in 1970 the company averaged Dollars 100 in income per 1,000 board feet of
lumber sold, it now averages over Dollars 1,000. However, as its own harvest
narrows, MacMil- lan is engaging more and more in lumber merchandising, a
lower margin business.
The company is also looking beyond the coastal rainforest, and is
aggressively pursuing 'engineered' wood that may eventually replace old
timber for structural uses.
In 1991 it entered a joint venture with a US firm to form Trus Joist
MacMillan, which currently produces four different manufactured wood
products in 14 plants across the US, and has global marketing reach. With
only Dollars 300m in annual sales, the venture is far from outpacing
MacMillan's more conven- tional operations.
MacMillan Bloedel's Vancouver-based management got a new set of shareholders
in February when Noranda Forest, which for 12 years had owned the
controlling interest in 'MacBlo,' sold out in a public offering to investors
in Canada and Europe.
The sale allowed MacMillan to cut free of the financial uncertainties
associated with Noranda, a subsidiary of the debt-plagued Hees-Edper
corporate empire owned by Canada's Bronfman family.
The 55.5m-share, CDollars 1bn offering was oversubscribed, despite the fact
that MacMillan Bloedel, squeezed by declining pulp and paper prices and
rising environmental costs, is coming out of two years of losses. Buyers
took the stock in three-part instalment receipts, for the equivalent of
Canadian Dollars 17.50.
Analysts say the shares were popular because they are an indirect investment
in the rocketing lumber market, and a gamble that newsprint prices may be
near bottom.
Mr John Johnson, a Vancouver-based lumber industry analyst for Richardson
Greenshields, forecasts 1993 earnings at 70 cents per share, and 1994
earnings of Dollars 1.50 per share, a big improvement over the company's
Dollars 48.8m or 42 cents per share loss in 1992.
However, with the company's stock price now above Dollars 20 and lumber
prices off their February peak, Mr Johnson has downgraded his recommendation
on the stock to a 'hold', from a 'buy.' The company squeaked out an
operating profit of about CDollars 7.3m in the first quarter, the first in
nine quarters.
Mr Findlay is realistic about the full-year outlook, saying it will mirror
the first quarter. 'Up, but nothing spectacular,' he says, noting the
company will benefit from better prices for lumber and cost controls in pulp
and paper.
The unprofitable pulp and newsprint business represents more than 50 per
cent of MacMillan Bloedel's Dollars 3.5bn in assets. Mr Findlay says the
company has made remarkable strides in becoming more competitive in those
areas. However, the overburdened pulp market is beyond his control. 'It will
come around in time. In this type of industry you have to weather the
storm,' he says.
In British Columbia's mountainous forests, MacMillan Bloedel is king, but it
is dwarfed by other North American forest products companies such as
Weyerhaeuser. It does not dominate any of its industries, and is subject to
pressures from lower cost producers in most of its business segments.
The company's pulp and paper revenues fell to Dollars 819m last year, for an
operating loss of Dollars 8.6m. Since 1988 its newsprint production has
dropped 34 per cent, and market pulp production is down 24 per cent. Just as
pulp prices began to slump, Canada imposed strict clean water regulations on
pulp mills, forcing a Dollars 350m effluent control programme on MacMillan
Bloedel,which has diverted investment capital from other areas.
'That was a capital investment that did not generate income,' notes Mr Eric
Lauritzen, MacMillan Bloedel vice president for pulp and paper marketing.
But he says some of the environmental costs were offset by plant
rationalisations and labour negotiations that reduced worker costs.
He points to a modest rise in newsprint costs last quarter as an indicator
that the pulp and paper recession may be moderating. With the pulp business
heavily dependent on exports to Europe, he expects prices to improve only
after capacity shake-outs and a European economic recovery. Both, he
concedes, will take time.
MacMillan Bloedel also has exposure to Europe through its 16 per cent
ownership of one of the continent's largest paper companies, NV Koninklijke
KNP, which last quarter merged with two other Netherlands companies to form
KNP BT. MacMillan recorded a Dollars 5.7m loss on its KNP BT stake in the
first quarter.
</TEXT>
