<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / UK Company News: BP's shares rise as first quarter pleases
City
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Petroleum surprised the City in reporting better-than-expected first
quarter profits of Pounds 231m - before exceptional items - on a replacement
cost basis, compared with Pounds 73m.
The shares rose 10p to 306p.
Mr David Simon, chief executive, said the improvement in profits for the
three months to March 31 had largely been a result of 'self help'. He said
trading conditions had been tough and although BP had maintained sales,
margins were lower.
BP's cost-cutting exercise generated surplus cashflow of Pounds 600m in the
first quarter, allowing the company to pay down debt and reduce its
debt-to-equity ratio from 99 per cent at the end of last year to 94 per
cent.
Mr Simon said the company had paid off Dollars 1.8bn (Pounds 1.16bn) of debt
since the middle of last year, leaving a burden of Dollars 14.5bn.
He warned, however, that cashflow in the second quarter would be adversely
affected by Dollars 630m tax due to the Alaskan government and lower
divestment proceeds, although refining margins had recently improved.
A decline in the oil price and a drop in refining margins had led to a
downturn of Dollars 150m in income, Mr Simon pointed out. However, that had
been more than offset by lower costs and an improvement in the
dollar-sterling rate.
While BP's sales of refined products were up by 6 per cent in the first
quarter and gas sales rose by 2 per cent, refining margins fell 50 cents in
Europe and 30 cents in the US.
'These results are quite good, because BP is moving to a perfectly
respectable level of earnings when the environment is not improving at all,
in fact it is deteriorating,' said Mr Nick Antill, analyst at Hoare Govett,
the stockbroker.
The company's overall replacement cost profit - which strips out gains and
losses from oil stocks - was up from Pounds 200m in the final quarter last
year. The contribution to operating profit from exploration and production
held steady from the fourth quarter at Pounds 516m, against Pounds 515m, in
spite of a Dollars 1.50 a barrel drop in the oil price. A year ago the
contribution was Pounds 414m.
Refining and marketing achieved profits of Pounds 124m (Pounds 36m), up from
Pounds 117m in the fourth quarter. Chemicals showed a loss of Pounds 14m
against loses of Pounds 6m a year earlier and Pounds 22m in the fourth
quarter. Earnings in the first quarter increased from 1.4p to 4.3p while the
dividend is cut to 2.1p (4.2p).
See Lex
</TEXT>
