<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Argentaria issue oversubscribed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ARGENTARIA, Spain's state-owned banking group, yesterday said the public
issue of 25 per cent of its shares to raise Pta120bn (Pounds 687bn) had
closed heavily oversubscribed.
Foreign interest was particularly high with international investors
subscribing for 10.6 times the shares on offer.
The oversubscription comes as the peseta is under pressure and when
potential political instability is forecast in Spain ahead of the June 6
general election.
Argentaria is placing only 39 per cent (Pta41.8bn) of the total 25 per cent
equity offering outside Spain but international demand for the banking
group's paper totalled Pta445bn - slightly less than the Pta476bn at which
the offer values the whole group.
In Spain, where 61 per cent of the offering will be placed, domestic
institutions and retail investors oversubscribed by 4.6 times. Demand in the
retail tranche totalled Pta206bn against the Pta55.1bn offered.
More than 370,000 small domestic investors applied for paper, a total that
automatically gave Argentaria the biggest share register of any Spanish
banking institution.
Argentaria shares will start trading in Madrid, New York and London on May
12. Analysts believe a big proportion of the domestically held equity could
end up abroad.
The issue has been globally co-ordinated by Morgan Stanley of the US and
Argentaria is able to distribute the international tranche on the basis of
quality of demand for its shares.
Success of the offering has been largely due to investor approval of the
Argentaria management team headed by chairman, Mr Francisco Luzon. 'There is
a general feeling that this a clean, tough team creating an efficiency
story,' said an executive of one of lead banks.
</TEXT>
