<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Watchdog may seek curbs on unsuitable life sales
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LIFE insurance sales agents may be required to tell prospective customers
what they are allowed to sell, who pays them and the charges for each
product in graph form if proposals being considered by the Securities and
Investments Board go ahead.
SIB, the City's chief regulatory watchdog, yesterday released a study by
consultant Mr Tim Miller of possible new rules which would limit sales of
unsuitable products. An SIB study last year found that one quarter to one
third of all life insurance products were cancelled within the first two
years, leaving policy holders with little or no refund of premiums paid.
It is believed that high lapse rates of policies in early years are closely
linked to their sale to people for whom they are clearly unsuitable.
The centrepiece of the proposals is a chart which outlines at a glance what
the value of a policy is each year until it matures. Consumers would be
given a prospectus on the product and a chart setting out in numerical terms
the information in the graph. Customers would be able to see the effect of
cancelling a policy in each year until it matures.
Mr Miller's proposals address most of the objections to current rules raised
by an Office of Fair Trading report in March which said that the rules on
disclosure limited competition in the sale of life insurance and served
consumers badly.
Like the OFT, Mr Miller proposes that life companies should be required to
tell prospective customers their own charges for each product sold instead
of showing the average charge throughout the industry, as now.
Mr Miller's report stops short of proposing an OFT suggestion that
independent financial advisers should tell prospective customers how much
commission they will earn on each sale. He believes that requiring it would
clutter up the graphs.
SIB said yesterday it was considering Mr Miller's report along with that of
the OFT.
Prudential yesterday said it 'shared the objectives of clear disclosure in
ways which people will understand and that is something which needs to be
properly thought through and properly tested before being brought in'.
</TEXT>
