<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / French audit shows rising deficit in public finances
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BUCHAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A SPECIAL audit ordered by France's new Conservative government yesterday
confirmed the gaping hole in the country's public finances ahead of the
budget next week which is expected to raise taxes and cut spending.
The audit, conducted by Mr Jean Raynaud, a senior official of the state
accounting body, shows overall accumulated deficits in the budget and the
social security system rising to an estimated FFr475bn (Pounds 57.09bn) by
the end of this year. Most of the social security system is funded outside
the budget by contributions from employers and employees.
The audit assumes that the economy could contract by up to 1 per cent this
year. Basing itself on a median forecast of a 0.4 per cent drop in gross
domestic product, it says the recession's effect in depressing tax receipts
and raising social spending could increase the budget deficit from FFr226bn
last year to FFr341bn this year.
Such a deficit would amount to 4.8 per cent of France's national output,
well above the 3 per cent guideline in the Maastricht treaty on monetary
union. This in turn explains prime minister Edouard Balladur's recent
comment that any talk of accelerating the Maastricht currency union
timetable was a 'pious wish', given the state of public finance in France
and many other EC countries. He said his aim was to cut France's deficit to
less than 3 per cent by 1996-97.
Mr Raynaud, a long-time friend of the new prime minister, denied his report
sought to pin blame on the previous Socialist government. Nevertheless, one
Socialist MP accused the government of 'polemicising' the country's
financial problems.
This year's still-larger budget deficit will be the result of reduced tax
revenue (FFr120bn lower than first forecast) and higher spending (an extra
FFr55bn, much of it on temporary work schemes), the report calculates.
The Raynaud audit says the deficit in France's social security system was
'unprecedented'. The accumulated deficit of the pension, health and family
allowances funds will rise to nearly FFr100bn by the end of 1993.
In addition, the unemployment insurance scheme could go bankrupt next month
unless the state tops up it up.
French rates cut, Page 3
</TEXT>
