FT  07 MAY 93 / Observer: Geography lesson
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Meanwhile, digging into the Soviet past in the course of a 10-part series
entitled The World That Came in from the Cold, the BBC World Service
purports to have unearthed some remarkable facts.
One of the more far-fetched anecdotes hails from a Budapest civil servant
who recalls how Soviet troops, summoned to quash the November 4 1956
uprising, emerged from their tanks - when the fighting was done - asking for
directions to the ocean. Crestfallen to find no briny, one of their number
explained that they thought they were shooting the British in Suez.
Well, Shakespeare's grasp of geography was a little ropy too. Remember The
Winter's Tale, where Bohemia is by the seaside?
