<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / The Property Market: The reluctant landlord - Hanson's
acquisitions in the 1980s have helped it build one of the UK's biggest
property banks
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
With some Pounds 4bn of assets, Hanson, the Anglo-US conglomerate, is
Britain's second biggest property company, according to a survey last year
by DTZ Debenham Thorpe. But it is a reluctant corporate landowner. 'We never
went out and bought a property company. We have acquired property by
default,' says Mr Malcolm Ablett, managing director of Hanson Properties.
Apart from a brief flirtation last summer with the notion of buying Canary
Wharf, the troubled Olympia and York development in London, Hanson has
rarely set out to add to its property portfolio in the UK or the US, where
it also has substantial assets. Instead, it has built up its property assets
through an aggressive policy of acquisitions of non-property companies.
These began in 1983 with the purchase of London Brick, which owned large
clay and gravel reserves and agricultural estates of some 100,000 acres in
south-east England.
In the same year, Hanson bought UDS, a retail group with a portfolio of
2,000 stores. These included Whiteleys department store in west London,
which at the time was trading at a loss. Hanson closed Whiteleys, won
planning permission for a redevelopment and sold the site to Arlington for
Pounds 18m.
In 1985, Hanson took over the Imperial Group, which brought with it, among
other things, the Courage brewing estate. The estate included the site of
Shakespeare's Globe theatre in Southwark, along with a adjacent terrace of
listed Georgian houses. The future of this historically important site has
provoked intense controversy (even though the most controversial proposal of
all - a plan by American tycoon Donald Trump to build an 80-storey office
tower on the site - was never pursued).
The development of the Globe site has been stymied by a debate among
conservationists over whether to destroy the Georgian houses so as to
excavate the remains of the Globe. At present, the anti-excavation camp, is
winning the argument; Hanson may find new uses for the Georgian houses,
either as flats or a hotel. Meanwhile the back of the site is due to be
turned into a car park.
In 1989 Hanson bought Consolidated Gold Fields, which through its subsidiary
ARC, an aggregates company, owned a property development arm and gravel
pits. The most recent addition to Hanson's holdings came with the 1991
acquisition of Beazer, the building products group. The Beazer purchase
brought with it a large estate management business and investment portfolio.
Hanson is not sentimental about its large property bank. 'Our sole objective
is to turn assets into cash,' says Mr Ablett.
Some portfolios have been sold in their entirety; the UDS stores were sold
long ago; as was the village of Stewartby near Bedford, which was built by
London Brick. Others are proving more difficult to sell. As a result of the
Beazer and ARC takeovers, for instance, Hanson inherited three empty office
blocks in Bracknell, one of the most over-developed towns in the south-east.
Before its takeover by Hanson, ARC had also undertaken a lot of business
park development, which came to fruition just when recession took hold in
1989. 'The timing was terrible,' says Mr Ablett. Hanson has also held onto
most of the investment portfolio, including shopping centres, it inherited
from ARC and Beazer. Hanson is likely to start selling its shopping centres
following the recent pick-up in interest in this sector of the market.
Hanson owns shopping centres in Bath, Stroud and Newcastle and has stakes in
centres in Middlesborough, Leeds and Hull.
The most significant of Hanson's remaining assets is its land bank: 100,000
acres of land in the south-east, which belonged to ARC and London Brick.
Selling the land will take a long time. First, Hanson does not want to flood
the market. Second, it wants to add value to its land bank by winning
planning permission before putting it on the market.
The case for addressing planning questions has become more urgent as a
result of recent changes to the planning regime, which lay down the
framework for planning decisions for the next 10 years. 'We do not want to
miss the boat,' says Mr Ablett.
The most recent planning exercise undertaken by Hanson was a nine-month
review of ARC's land holdings. Each parcel of land had to be examined and
reviewed for its development potential. 'We recovered the cost of the review
in its eighth or ninth week,' says Mr Ablett.
But Hanson's most elaborate exercise in adding value to its land is at
Peterborough, where it owns a large area of land left derelict following the
extraction of brick clay. After eight years of preparatory work, it has won
planning permission for the Pounds 500m Peterborough Southern Township - the
largest private-sector new town since the first stages of Welwyn Garden
City.
On the 2,000-acre site, Hanson has planning consent for 3m square feet of
commercial and industrial space, a retail park, two supermarkets and housing
for 13,000 people. Hanson says it has already had some interest from
developers, mostly for warehouses. None the less, it expects the development
of the township to take more than a decade.
'We have to be realistic,' says Mr Ablett. 'We realise this is a longer term
project. It won't produce vast sums in the short term.' Although Hanson
Properties usually shuns development, it does not rule out joint venture
developments. 'It may be that to kick-start the project, we have to be
flexible. We are prepared to talk to anyone.'
If and when a partner is selected for the Peterborough venture, it is
unlikely to be the Beazer housebuilding arm. The Hanson divisions are kept
at arms' length; no division is asked to subsidise another. 'We don't
believe in robbing Peter to pay Paul,' says Mr Ablett.
Hanson Properties is also heavily involved in trying to extract value from
the land used within its businesses. The efficient management of property is
central to the philosophy of a company which prides itself on gaining
maximum value from its assets.
Reviews of operational assets are made at a local level, although there are
instances where Hanson Properties would become involved 'to help their
management thinking'.
That said, Mr Ablett is anxious to dispel any notion that the property arm
is a significant overhead for Hanson. The property management is contracted
out to agents, while the head office employs just 30 property staff,
including accountants and secretaries.
The overriding impression given by Hanson is that property is as much a
painful necessity as a potential source of value. 'We are not long-term
holders of property,' says Mr Ablett. 'Our role is to convert what we have
into cash, not to add to it.'
 -----------------------------------------------------------------------
