<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Generator may halve cost of clean-up
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, Scottish Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SCOTTISHPOWER, the privatised Scottish electricity company, believes it can
nearly halve the projected cost of reducing emissions of sulphur dioxide, a
main cause of acid rain, from its coal-burning power station at Longannet on
the Firth of Forth.
It also said yesterday that it was to spend Pounds 24m on equipment which
would produce less nitrogen oxide and remove dust from flue gases at the
plant.
The company is soon to apply for planning permission to install flue-gas
desulphurisation (FGD) equipment at Longannet. It put the cost 'in excess of
Pounds 200m'. This compares with figures of between Pounds 350m and Pounds
400m quoted in its prospectus for flotation in 1991.
ScottishPower intends to use an FGD system called seawater scrubbing instead
of the more common system which uses gypsum to remove sulphur from flue
gases. Seawater scrubbing has not been used in Britain before, partly
because none of the plants where FGD is being installed are on the coast.
The company, which yesterday launched its new environmental policy, has to
meet standards on emissions set by the government in line with targets laid
down by the European Community. In 1990 the government decided that 8,000 MW
of UK generating capacity should be fitted with FGD equipment.
Yesterday Mr Mike Smith, ScottishPower's chief operating officer with
responsibility for environmental issues, said: 'We have pointed out to the
government on a number of occasions that it would achieve greater
environmental benefit if FGD was applied to more stations in England rather
than applied to us.' This is because ScottishPower's plants partly burn
Scottish coal, which has a lower sulphur content than other supplies.
</TEXT>
