<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Submission warns on dangers of
overload
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TEACHERS' submission attacks 'excessive prescription and content
overload'. It warns against the 'danger of an ad hoc, subject-by-subject
revision which would inevitably lead to a lack of coherence and possible
overload'.
The proposals follow three headings:
An overall view
The teachers say it is 'almost universally accepted' that the curriculum in
its present form takes up too much time to be balanced and broadly-based.
'Drastic pruning' of the requirements for each of the foundation subjects is
essential.
At each of its four key age ranges it should concentrate on 'the basics'.
General principles would include religious education, and 'the highest
priority must be given to reading, writing and basic computation' for
seven-year-olds.
Assessment
'Many technical flaws remain.' The teachers say this is because the
procedure 'suffers from attempting to combine too many features into one
system'. These include attempting to measure accurately each child's
attainment across an 'enormous range of attainment targets', while using the
tests in a diagnostic way 'although the timing of the tests and information
obtained from them are not appropriate for this purpose'. They say
assessment must 'support not dominate the curriculum', and take full account
of continuous assessment by teachers.
The review process
The teachers want a planned and predictable cycle, or 'shelf life' for
reviewing the content of each subject within the curriculum. This would curb
the secretary of state's current power to order revisions whenever it is
deemed appropriate.
Reviews of a subject would start two years before the end of its shelf life.
Evidence would be taken from inspectors' reports, teachers and other groups,
and proposals would be drafted by a group including teachers, inspectors,
and the Department for Education, before being presented to the secretary of
state. The proposals would then undergo two stages of statutory
consultation, before being finalised by the secretary of state.
The submission was jointly drafted by the six unions and endorsed by the
National Association of Teachers in Further and Higher Education, and five
organisations of independent schools: the Girls' Schools Association, the
Headmasters' Conference, the Incorporated Association of Preparatory
Schools, the Independent Schools Association Incorporated, and the Society
of Headmasters and Headmistresses in Independent Schools.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9411 Administration of Educational Programs.
</IN>
