<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour wrangle over VAT
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS and IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
INTERNAL wrangling over economic policy left the Labour leadership
embarrassed yesterday as the government seized on an article by a party
spokesman suggesting the ending of VAT zero rating for all items.
Lord Desai, Labour economic spokesman in the House of Lords, also argued
that Labour 'should oppose spending cuts but be bold in proposing suitably
packaged tax increases'.
Senior party figures sought to play down the significance of the remarks but
the insistance of Mr Gordon Brown, Treasury spokesman, that Labour was
opposed to extending VAT to food, children's clothing, fuel and transport,
only highlighted tensions over the party's economic strategy.
To the annoyance of some Labour MPs the party opposes tax increases but also
complains about cuts in public spending. A revised tax and spending policy
will depend on the outcome of the independent commission on social justice
set up by Mr John Smith, party leader.
Lord Desai, writing in the left-wing Tribune newspaper, said: 'It is time to
debate whether Labour favours a high spending and high taxation policy,
balancing the budget over the cycle, or whether it is always for high
spending and low taxation.'
He added: 'The latter alternative, although attractive, is in the long run
neither economically rational nor politically credible.'
Lord Desai said Labour had to think about taxation that would hit
consumption by the better-off. He favoured higher band income tax and ending
of the ceiling on national insurance contributions, proposed in Labour's
1992 election manifesto.
'Failing that, I would remove zero rating for VAT on all items.' Benefit
entitlements could be doubled to compensate the poor, he added.
At Treasury questions, Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, taunted Labour over
the Lord Desai article: 'I think the whole country and the House will
observe that the Labour party seems to have one policy in the House of
Commons and another policy in the House of Lords.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P8651 Political Organizations.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
