<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lamont upbeat on recovery prospects
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IN ANOTHER upbeat assessment of the outlook for the economy Mr Norman
Lamont, the chancellor, told the Commons yesterday 'the prospects for
sustained recovery are good'.
He emphasised that both inflation and the rate of increase in earnings were
at their lowest level for 25 years, while productivity in manufacturing
industry was increasing sharply.
Mr Lamont acknowledged the need for 'firm control' over public expenditure
in responding to concern expressed by government backbenchers and opposition
MPs about the size of the public sector borrowing requirement.
Stressing the need to bring the PSBR down, he assured the House that it was
'a very high priority' for the government.
Ms Clare Short (Lab Birmingham Ladywood) accused the chancellor of 'pushing
up' the sterling exchange rate and warned that it might result in the
recovery being lost.
Mr Lamont retorted: 'The pound is floating and we have no exchange rate
target'.
Further cuts in interest rates were urged by Mr Austin Mitchell (Lab Great
Grimsby), who said the government should stop trying to 'talk the pound up
again'.
Mr Michael Portillo, chief secretary to the Treasury, told Mr Mitchell not
to put his faith in devaluation, which had never been a way out of Britain's
problems.
Underlining the importance of competitiveness, Mr Portillo said it was
'extremely encouraging' that while unit wage costs were falling in Britain
they were continuing to rise in Japan and Germany.
Mr Alistair Darling, Labour's frontbench City spokesman, called on the
government to condemn the 'exorbitant' Pounds 10m a year reportedly received
by a Royal Bank of Scotland executive while others less well off were being
urged to take little or no increase in their pay.
While refusing to comment on individual salaries, Sir John Cope, the
paymaster general, insisted that ministers had set an example which he would
like to see followed by others in industry and commerce.
</TEXT>
