<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / BCCI depositors win compensation ruling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MASON, Law Courts Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A LEGAL device used by a group of BCCI depositors to increase many-fold the
compensation they received following the collapse of the bank was declared
legal yesterday by the Court of Appeal.
The scheme - used by a group of about 60 depositors - involved splitting the
money held on deposit into individual lots of Pounds 20,000 and then
formally transferring the ownership of these to trusted family members or
friends.
The depositors were able to claim Pounds 15,000 for each lot - the maximum
small investors' compensation for deposits of Pounds 20,000 or less - under
the Deposit Protection Scheme, which is designed to alleviate hardship when
a bank becomes insolvent.
The overall sum required to meet payments due to all BCCI depositors under
the protection scheme is about Pounds 78m. It is estimated that the
splitting device will cost the Deposit Protection Board about Pounds 3.7m.
By a two-to-one majority, Lord Justice Russell, sitting with Lord Justice
Simon Brown and Sir Michael Fox, dismissed appeals by the Deposit Protection
Board and Barclays Bank against a ruling by the Vice Chancellor Sir Donald
Nicholls in July last year upholding the scheme's legality.
The judges also refused the Deposit Protection Board and Barclays leave to
appeal to the House of Lords over the issue.
The scheme was devised by a firm of north London accountants, Pearlman,
Kahan and Joseph. It operated in July 1991 before the government blocked its
use by passing legislation.
Mr Keith Kahan, one of the firm's partners, said: 'We are delighted with the
ruling. About 60 original BCCI depositors split their money. Most of them
were small depositors who made assignments to their wives and children and
they will be the ones who benefit.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Bank of Credit and Commerce International.
</CO>
<XX>
