<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Ruling curbs cuts in pension scheme benefits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LONDON Regional Transport could be forced to pay up to Pounds 93m into its
pension scheme following a High Court ruling on Tuesday unless it can reach
an agreement with members on improving benefits.
In a key ruling, Mr Justice Knox said that LRT could not alter the terms of
its pension scheme without taking account of benefits implied, but not
specifically promised. According to pensions experts the ruling places clear
limits for the first time on an employer's right to cut pension costs by
restructuring pension schemes.
The judge has directed all parties to the case - the trustees, the
pensioners, the active members and LRT - to reach a negotiated settlement.
Lawyers for the parties believe such a settlement may not require LRT to add
funds to the scheme directly, but it could be forced to set a minimum
contributions rate for itself, cut employees contributions and enhance
benefits out of existing surplus for present and deferred pensioners.
Mr Justice Knox ruled that where pension schemes are merged to create a new
scheme, not only must actual benefits to members not be substantially
worsened, but unwritten promises of benefits must be recognised. It is the
first time the courts have so unequivocally protected the expectations of
pension benefits.
There are some legal quirks in the case which are unique to the LRT pension
scheme, but many pensions experts believe the case will set a precedent. 'It
has widespread implications for members of ordinary occupational pension
schemes,' said Mr John Cunliffe, partner at McKenna and Co, who represented
the 45,000 present and deferred pensioners.
In 1989 two LRT schemes were merged into a new scheme via a statutory act of
parliament. The RMT rail union questioned, among other things, whether the
merger had been legally carried out, and whether it was right that LRT could
change the rules to eliminate the requirement that its own annual
contribution be 2 1/3 times that of the employees.
In the new scheme LRT contributions are determined by how much is needed to
pay the specified level of benefits.
The change in the LRT contribution rate meant that it could take a valuable
partial contributions holiday, reducing the Pounds 460m surplus by Pounds
93m.
Mr Justice Knox did not address the question of whether an employer is
entitled to use surplus. But he said that the existence of that surplus had
given rise to members' expectations that benefits would be enhanced, as
indeed they had in the years before the merger.
'No doubt the larger the surplus the livelier the expectation but in the
majority of cases it remains an expectation rather than a right. That is not
to say that it is either without value or that the law will not protect it
in appropriate circumstances,' Mr Justice Knox said.
Mr Edward Cooper, partner at solicitors Russell, Jones and Walker, which
represented the RMT union members, said that some ambiguities about the case
could affect its applicability to ordinary occupational schemes. Unlike most
mergers which are effected by trustees, this merger occurred through a
statutory act of parliament.
The Confederation of British Industry yesterday called on the government to
abandon its effort to force occupational pension schemes to increase
benefits in line with infla-tion.
Speaking at the annual conference of the National Association of Pension
Funds in Harrogate, North Yorkshire, yesterday, Mr Robbie Gilbert said the
new law would add considerably to company pension costs.
</TEXT>
