<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Virgin takes BA 'dirty tricks' war to court
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS, Aerospace Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
VIRGIN Atlantic Airways yesterday launched High Court proceedings against
British Airways following the failure of the two airlines to settle their
long-running 'dirty tricks' dispute.
Mr Richard Branson, Virgin's chairman, said the airlines were now 'at war'.
Virgin's writ against BA alleges copyright infringement, breach of
confidence and misuse of confidential information.
Speaking from Arizona, Mr Branson said Virgin had attempted for the past
four months to reach a compromise with BA. But he said the situation had
turned into a farce and it was now time for the courts to decide.
BA said it regretted that Virgin had discontinued settlement discussions.
'BA has made it clear that any liability which it may have will be met in
full', it added in a brief statement.
The High Court action relates to Virgin's allegations that its bigger UK
rival accessed Virgin passenger details and information as well as data
concerning aircraft and load factors relating to flights and associated
passenger and travel services.
Virgin said the proceedings were only the first of several other legal and
regulatory steps it proposed taking against BA in various jurisdictions
including the US and the European Community.
After BA agreed to pay Virgin Pounds 610,000 in libel damages and apologised
'unreservedly' in the High Court in January, Mr Branson warned he intended
to take further legal action if he did not secure adequate compensation for
the commercial damage he said Virgin suffered as a result of BA's 'dirty
tricks' campaign.
Involved negotiations between the airlines broke down on March 19 after
Virgin rejected a Pounds 9m cash compensation offer because of what Mr
Branson claimed was an un-acceptable 'vow of silence' demanded by BA.
Relations worsened following a television programme last week renewing
allegations that top BA directors were aware of their airline's campaign
against Virgin.
After the programme, Mr Branson challenged Sir Colin Marshall, BA's
chairman, and Mr Robert Ayling, the airline's managing director, to resign
or sue the television programme.
Sir Michael Angus, BA's deputy chairman, subsequently sent a brief note to
Mr Branson with a copy of a statement by the BA board to the airline's staff
giving its full backing to Sir Colin and Mr Ayling.
It said the board did not question the integrity of the two executives. 'The
view of directors is that any claims which Mr Branson thinks he may have
should be stated in the appropriate courts and be evaluated after full
consideration of all the evidence.'
Mr Branson said yesterday Virgin intended to subpoena Sir Colin, Mr Ayling,
and Mr Liam Strong, BA's former head of marketing and operations and now
chief executive of Sears, one of Britain's biggest high-street retailers, to
force them to give evidence in the High Court.
</TEXT>
