<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Howard set to face his critics: Carbon targets are attacked
as unrealistic
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL How-ard, environment secretary, will open a government conference
today on how Britain should meet international targets to combat global
warming and will face accusations that government emission forecasts are
unrealistic and keep changing.
Mr Norman Lamont said in his Budget statement that Britain had put in place
measures to get two thirds of the way towards the target of stabilising
carbon dioxide emissions at 1990 levels by the year 2000. According to
government forecasts the UK needs to cut emissions by 10m tonnes of carbon
(mtC) to a level of 160mtC.
Workshops organised by the Department of the Environment in preparation for
today's conference in London came to the conclusion that the 10mtC figure
was too low.
The main concern to come out of the workshops, which included industrialists
and environmentalists, was that emissions were forecast to rise steeply
after the end of the decade, largely due to rising traffic levels.
The workshops have also sent to Mr Howard their view that the voluntary
basis of present government schemes is inadequate.
Environmentalists are likely to question today why the Department of the
Environment has issued several conflicting sets of figures since the Budget
to explain how the 10mtC target will be met.
In evidence to the Commons environment committee on Wednesday the Department
of the Environment said the newly formed Energy Saving Trust and information
and education schemes would contribute savings of 2mtC to 3.5mtC this
decade.
This indicates a larger role for the trust, which is intended to encourage
households to save energy, than the department forecast soon after the
Budget, when it predicted a saving of 2.5mtC.
The department's estimate of the part played by new building regulations has
also fallen in the past two months, from 0.5mtC to 0.25mtC, according to its
evidence.
Mr Andrew Warren, director of the Association for the Conservation of
Energy, said: 'We had the initial commitment from the chancellor, reiterated
by the prime minister, and it now seems that they are juggling the figures
between different programmes to make them add up.'
The Department of the Environment said yesterday: 'The figures given on
Wednesday are our latest estimates.'
The trust's prominent role has sparked scepticism from environmentalists and
from the utility companies. It announced its first scheme this week after
taking more than a year to set itself up.
</TEXT>
