<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / Insolvency profession found wanting
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER, Property Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MOST PROPERTY lenders do not believe that the insolvency profession provides
value for money, a survey by Chesterton, a firm of chartered surveyors,
shows
Almost two thirds of the 60 financial institutions questioned said they had
not received good value.
Some lenders were also dissatisfied with the service provided by receivers
and administrators. Just over one in five respondents described the service
from insolvency practitioners as poor, while 44 per cent described it as
fair and 30 per cent as good.
Mr Mark Homan, president of the Society of Practitioners of Insolvency, said
in response to the findings that in some straightforward cases insolvency
practitioners might not bring a great deal of added value. Property
insolvencies often involved extremely complex situations, however, where
there was a clear need for expertise.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
