<HEADLINE>
FT  07 MAY 93 / IG Metall extends strike
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY and QUENTIN PEEL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN, BONN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IG METALL, Germany's powerful engineering union, yesterday extended its
indefinite strike action to 13 more enterprises, with the ailing steel
industry particularly targeted.
More than 35,000 eastern German steel, metal and engineering workers from 70
enterprises are now on strike in support of higher wage claims. They are
demanding the reinstatement of a March 1991 contract, which Gesamtmetall,
the metal and engineering employers association, cancelled last month. The
contract was aimed at equalising eastern and western wages by next year.
Wages in eastern Germany are about 60 per cent of western German levels.
IG Metall said the strikes would continue, and spread. However, it said the
union would try to renew negotiations in the Saxon capital of Dresden which
had broken down earlier in the week.
Negotiations between the union and employers were due to start last night in
Rostock, in the northern state of Mecklenburg-West Pomerania, the heart of
the dwindling shipbuilding industry.
Industrial orders in the west German economy dropped another 3 per cent in
March, and seasonally adjusted unemployment rose in April, confirming that
the economic recession is still deepening, writes Quentin Peel in Bonn.
The only hopeful indicator was that the rate of increase in unemployment has
slowed slightly in the past month, but the headline figure for the country
as a whole remains above 3.3m.
</TEXT>
